<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_EigenvectorEigenvalue"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport xmlns="" href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Eigenvector / Eigenvalue: Example</title>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>With respect to standard coordinates of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math>, the <math>
                  <latex>(3,3)</latex>
               </math>-matrix <math>
                  <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
               </math> below describes the orthogonal projection of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> onto the <math>
                  <latex>xy</latex>
               </math>-plane.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display xmlns="">
				        <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]\quad \text{gives projection}\quad
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x \\ y \\ z
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x \\ y \\ 0
\end{array}
\right]

				</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>Relate its transformation properties to its eigenvectors and eigenvalues.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme xmlns="">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>To visualize this projection, imagine light shining vertically onto the <math>
                        <latex>xy</latex>
                     </math>-plane. Then the projection sends each object in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> to its shadow in the <math>
                        <latex>xy</latex>
                     </math>-planae.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore every vector in the <math>
                        <latex>xy</latex>
                     </math>-plane gets transformed into itself, that is a vector of the form <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v} = (x,y,0)</latex>
                     </math> gets transformed into</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A}\cdot \Vect{v} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x \\ y \\ 0
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x \\ y \\ 0
\end{array}
\right] = 1\cdot \Vect{v}

				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This means that every nonzero vector of the form <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v}=(x,y,0)</latex>
                     </math> is an eigenvector of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> with eigenvalue <math>
                        <latex>\lambda_1 = 1</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>On the other hand, this projection sends the entire <math>
                        <latex>z</latex>
                     </math>-axis to the <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>-vector, that is a vector of the form <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{w}=(0,0,z)</latex>
                     </math> gets transformed into</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A}\cdot \Vect{w} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 0 \\ z
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 0 \\ 0
\end{array}
\right] = 0\cdot \Vect{w}

				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This means that every nonzero vector of the form <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{w} = (0,0,z)</latex>
                     </math> is an eigenvector of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> with eigenvalue <math>
                        <latex>\lambda_2=0</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>	
</showme.pack>
